{"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/FamiliarizeWithTypes"},"sections":[{"title":"Exploring Space's Types","kind":"hero","estimatedTimeInMinutes":20,"chapter":"Exploring Space's Types","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Space provides types that allow you to leverage the full potential of the SpaceVM.","type":"text"}]}]},{"tasks":[{"contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Writing code for blockchain involves operating within strict resource constraints. To address this, Space uses Swift’s “embedded” mode, ensuring the compiled code is as lightweight and efficient as possible.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"SpaceVM, the engine running smart contracts, limits heap allocations. As a result, types with dynamic sizes, such as Strings, Arrays, or classes, and any structs or enums containing these, are not permitted."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Additionally, Swift’s existential types—such as ","type":"text"},{"code":"any Protocol","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" where "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Protocol"},{"text":" is a protocol—are also forbidden. Existential types introduce runtime overhead, which is why they are not allowed in Space.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The allowed Swift types are:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"StaticString"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Integer types: Int, UInt, UInt8, UInt16, etc."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Bool: treated as a UInt8"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Space introduces specific types that serve as alternatives for those not allowed. This chapter introduces three key replacements:"}]},{"items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"Buffer","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":": A substitute for String and Data"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BigUint"},{"type":"text","text":": Capable of handling large unsigned integers"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"Vector","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":": An alternative to Array","type":"text"}]}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For security, these types do not feature mutating methods. Instead, they use methods that return new instances. For example, the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Buffer"},{"type":"text","text":" type does not include "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"append(_:) -> Void"},{"text":" but instead offers ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"appending(_:) -> Buffer"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}],"kind":"contentAndMedia"}],"title":"Handling Heap Allocation Challenges","stepsSection":[{"runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection1Step1.swift","type":"step","caption":[],"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Avoid using ","type":"text"},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" in Space, as it is prohibited due to memory restrictions."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Use ","type":"text"},{"code":"Buffer","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" as a fixed-size alternative for handling raw data and text."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[],"media":null,"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection1Step2.swift"},{"type":"step","code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection1Step3.swift","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Similarly, avoid using "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"type":"text","text":" since it leads to heap allocations and is not allowed."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Instead, leverage the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Vector"},{"text":" type as a memory-efficient alternative to ","type":"text"},{"code":"Array","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection1Step4.swift","type":"step","caption":[],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null},{"type":"step","caption":[],"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Integer types like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"code":"UInt","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", and ","type":"text"},{"code":"Bool","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" are fully supported and safe to use."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection1Step5.swift"},{"media":null,"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Ensure you only import the Space framework to keep the contract lightweight and efficient."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection1Step6.swift","runtimePreview":null}],"anchor":"Handling-Heap-Allocation-Challenges"},{"title":"Understanding the Buffer Type","contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"Buffer","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" is a fundamental type in Space, designed to store raw data and strings.","type":"text"}]}],"kind":"contentAndMedia"}],"anchor":"Understanding-the-Buffer-Type","stepsSection":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Start by creating the basic structure for your contract."}]}],"type":"step","media":null,"caption":[],"runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection2Step1.swift"},{"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection2Step2.swift","caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Important: Explicitly declare your variable as "},{"code":"Buffer","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to avoid being interpreted as ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Initialize a ","type":"text"},{"code":"Buffer","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" variable using a string literal.","type":"text"}]}],"media":null},{"caption":[],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Append another "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Buffer"},{"text":" to your existing variable.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection2Step3.swift","media":null,"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection2Step4.swift","type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Compare two ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Buffer"},{"type":"text","text":" instances. If they don’t match, throw a smart contract error."}]}],"caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Note: The ","type":"text"},{"code":"smartContractError","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" function requires a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Buffer"},{"type":"text","text":" parameter. This topic is covered in detail in a later chapter."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"anchor":"Working-with-the-BigUint-Type","title":"Working with the BigUint Type","contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","kind":"contentAndMedia","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Blockchains do not support decimal numbers. However, real-world applications often require decimal representation, such as in cryptocurrency amounts like 0.09281 Bitcoin."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To handle such cases, values are expressed as large numbers, with most tokens treating the first 18 trailing digits as decimals. For instance: 1 EGLD equals 1 * 10^18, or 1,000,000,000,000,000,000."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Standard Swift types, such as ","type":"text"},{"code":"UInt64","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", can only store values up to 18,446,744,073,709,551,615 (20 digits), making it impossible to represent values exceeding approximately 18.446744 EGLD.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Space provides the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BigUint"},{"type":"text","text":" type to store arbitrarily large positive numbers."}]}]}],"stepsSection":[{"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step1.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Begin by structuring your contract.","type":"text"}]}]},{"media":null,"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Declare a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BigUint"},{"type":"text","text":" constant with an integer literal."}]}],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step2.swift","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Important: You must specify the type explicitly as "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BigUint"},{"text":", or it will default to ","type":"text"},{"code":"Int","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]},{"runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step3.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Create a new "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BigUint"},{"type":"text","text":" by adding 3 to the previous constant."}]}],"caption":[],"type":"step","media":null},{"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step4.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Multiply the new variable by 7.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[]},{"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step5.swift","media":null,"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Add three times the initial constant to the new variable."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null,"caption":[]},{"media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Subtract 21 from the variable."}]}],"type":"step","caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Note: A ","type":"text"},{"code":"BigUint","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" value cannot be negative. If the subtraction results in a value below zero, Space will trigger a smart contract error."}]}],"runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step6.swift"},{"media":null,"caption":[],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step7.swift","type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Verify that the result is a multiple of 10, and throw a smart contract error if not."}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"runtimePreview":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection3Step8.swift","type":"step","caption":[],"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Ensure the result is greater than zero, throwing an error if it isn’t."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null}]},{"stepsSection":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Begin by setting up the basic structure of your contract."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection4Step1.swift","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null,"type":"step"},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Declare a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Vector"},{"type":"text","text":" variable to hold "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BigUint"},{"text":" elements.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection4Step2.swift","runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Important: Currently, array literal assignment is disabled. The Space team is investigating its impact on memory management in smart contracts before enabling it.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Add elements to the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Vector"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection4Step3.swift","runtimePreview":null,"media":null},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Iterate over the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Vector"},{"text":" to sum all the elements.","type":"text"}]}],"media":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection4Step4.swift","runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Important: The ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"for ... in"},{"text":" loop for vectors is currently disabled. The Space team is evaluating its effect on smart contract memory before enabling it.","type":"text"}]}]},{"caption":[],"type":"step","code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection4Step5.swift","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Ensure the sum equals 13. Throw a smart contract error if it doesn’t."}]}]}],"anchor":"Working-with-the-Vector-Type","title":"Working with the Vector Type","contentSection":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"type":"text","text":" type is often the default for storing dynamic-size data, but it is not permitted in Space. Fortunately, Space provides a suitable alternative: "},{"code":"Vector","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A "},{"code":"Vector","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" can store any type compatible with Space, including user-defined structs and enums."}]}],"mediaPosition":"trailing","kind":"contentAndMedia"}]},{"title":"Creating Your Own Types","contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","kind":"contentAndMedia","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can define your own structures and enumerations and make them compatible with Space using the "},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" annotation. When a type is marked with "},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", it becomes eligible to be used as input or output for endpoints, within arrays, and anywhere Space’s encoding system is applied.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A type annotated with "},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" must only contain fields of types compatible with Space, such as integers, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Bool"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"code":"Buffer","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"code":"BigUint","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Vector"},{"text":", and other ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" types."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Additionally, the ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" annotation prevents the structure from having methods or initializers."}]}]}],"stepsSection":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Start by creating a struct with fields that are compatible with Space.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","caption":[],"media":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection5Step1.swift","runtimePreview":null},{"media":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection5Step2.swift","runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Annotate your struct with ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to make it usable with Space’s encoding system.","type":"text"}]}],"caption":[]},{"caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use the "},{"code":"@Codable","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"-annotated type within your smart contracts.","type":"text"}]}],"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection5Step3.swift","media":null,"runtimePreview":null},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Remember, a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Codable"},{"type":"text","text":" type can be used as a field in other "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Codable"},{"type":"text","text":" types."}]}],"caption":[],"runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"code":"FamiliarizeWithTypesSection5Step4.swift","type":"step"}],"anchor":"Creating-Your-Own-Types"}],"kind":"tasks"},{"kind":"callToAction","action":{"type":"reference","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"text":"Get started","type":"text"}],"isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Get started","identifier":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/StoreValues"},"featuredEyebrow":"Tutorial","abstract":[{"text":"Each time a smart contract is invoked, it runs a single operation. The contract is temporarily loaded into the SpaceVM memory, the operation is executed, and then the contract is removed from memory.","type":"text"}],"title":"Persist Values Between Executions"}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space","doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/Deep-Dive-into-Space-Concepts","doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/Deep-Dive-into-Space-Concepts\/Exploring-Space's-Types"]],"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space","modules":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/Getting-Started\/Installing-the-Tools","projects":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/InstallingTools","sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/InstallingTools#Installing-Spaces-Dependencies","kind":"task"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/InstallingTools#Setting-Up-the-Space-CLI","kind":"task"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/InstallingTools#Initializing-and-Compiling-Your-First-Smart-Contract","kind":"task"}]}]},{"projects":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/CodingYourFirstContract","sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/CodingYourFirstContract#Initializing-the-Project","kind":"task"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Space\/tutorials\/Space\/CodingYou